ndoor training facility s architects  HKS and Commonwealth Architects  were awarded the Merit Award for Excellence in Architecture for the project April 16 by the Richmond chapter of the American Institute of Architects  Work is also under way to stabilize the historic Knights of Pythias building  moved to its current location on Main Street in October to make way for construction of the Indoor Training Facility  Repairs to the interior  which had suffered substantial water damage  have already been completed  Supports were installed to stabilize compromised roof trusses  floor joists  and floor decking  Work is continuing to install a temporary cover over the entire galvanized metal roof to prevent additional water from entering the building  Once the building is secure from water entry  fans will be installed to keep the building properly ventilated  and inspections will be conducted periodically to ensure that no additional damage occurs  The stabilization process is expected to be complete by the end of May  and the building then will be maintained as is indefinitely  VMI does not anticipate renovating the Pythias building for reuse until current construction projects are complete  To see more photos  visit the VMI Photo Blog    John Robertson IV and Maj  Sherri Tombarge    VMI Communications   Marketing News and Features Construction News Institute Report Photos   Videos Cindy Bither Administrative Assistant P   540  464 7207 F   540  464 7443 111 Smith Hall Lexington  VA 24450  Communications   Marketing News and Features Construction News Institute Report Photos   Videos Cindy Bither Administrative Assistant P   540  464 7207 F   540  464 7443 111 Smith Hall Lexington  VA 24450 Communications   Marketing News and Features Construction News Institute Report Photos   Videos Communications   Marketing Communications   Marketing News and Features News and Features Construction News Construction News Institute Report Institute Report Photos   Videos Photos   Video